title: For Sale/Trade:  The Gatshack Thing
postcontent: I really didn't want to get involved in any of this, but it's honestly a little ridiculous at this point.Yes, I personally feel that the image, demeanor, apparent philosophy, etc., Of Gat Shack is very unprofessional and may be a poor impression on both pro and anti firearm parties.That being said: I'm fuckin shocked at the amount of grown-ass adults that have devoted time, thought, and effort to bully a young shop owner on a website mainly dedicated to aid in legal local firearms sales and trades.I've seen multiple complaints about #GatShack filling up the 'for sale' sections with shit very few people seem interested in solely based on presentation, yet you combat this 'overcrowding' by posting multiple "listings" with the sole purpose of bullying some guy I highly doubt the majority of aggressors havery even seen offline.I get the complaints on how his presentation could set a negative standard for others, but i don't feel that bickering like children should be considered a more desirable image of the locals that might be allowed the responsibility of owning or even operating firearms.I honestly felt that the first listing addressing Gates Shack's presentation, etc., was relatively justifiable, though even that was more respectful and straightforward than this petty horse shit that I seem to see every other time I'm on here.If you don't like his shit, or dissagree with his business/advertising methods, buy from another retailer or personal seller, it's that easy. If you just can't contain the urge to bitch, whine, and bully, there are discussion threads available through the Armslist site where things like this would be less destructive to the sites purpose, though in my opinion even that would be a little depraved.In all honesty, and without knowing of this guy's past, morality, etc., it's safe to say he hasn't REALLY done anything to deserve this middle school behavior.I get that my posting this here is hypocritical to my point, but I'd hate for the site to change based on the actions of individuals stuck in a herd mentality, and throwing piss fits for general acceptance, or out of false justification. Don't mean to offend anyone on a personal level here, just want everyone to get past it, or take it to the section made specifically to avoid things like this.

title: For Sale:  Enfield No4 Mk1T sniper made by Long Branch in 1945
postcontent: This No4 Mk1* (T)sniper rifle was manufactured at the end of WWII by the Long Branch Arsenal during 1945 which manufactured a total of only 992 No4 Mk1* T's. It has matching serial numbers on the receiver, magazine, forearm and bolt. It has an excellent 25 inch 5 grooved bore with bright and sharp lands. The headspace is good on a 0.067" armourers gauge with a No '3' bolt head. The firing pin protrusion is 0.045 inch. The action is very good, tight and clean. The metal shows 99% of the blue finish with a little wear on the edges. It has a good BLO finish to the walnut stock with no cracks or major dings. The butt stock is stamped with the serial number of the scope it was set up with (1890 over another which is illegible). The scope mounts are original with no indications of the screws being re-locked (piened). The scope was produced by REL (Research Enterprises Ltd) with excellent optics and adjustments, complete with original leather lens cover with the broad arrow marking (maybe British as most Canadian equipment was marked C broad arrow). This appears to have been refurbished. Some witness marks of usage on the tube from the leather scope cups are present. The REL scopes were thought by some to be superior quality to the British scopes. The Brits may be excused as they were being bombed during production by the Germans. The wood forearm and hand guards are dark walnut wood. The rear hand guard has a arsenal repair applied at the rear. The butt stock is lighter in color and is stamped and painted with numerous numbers. The cheek piece appears to be of oak wood. This rifle has seen service in the Far East WWII theatre (India) from little patches of green paint on the metal which they used as a secondary protective. It has a serialized standard ten round magazine. This excellent condition is commensurate with one of the WW II Enfields' which has seventy years service. This will complete a collection with a rare Long Branch sniper.
